    <h2>Croydon — Large Eastern Suburb, Mixed Housing Eras, Gateway to the Ranges</h2>
    <div class="local-box"><p>Croydon is one of Melbourne's larger established eastern suburbs, spanning a wide area that includes Croydon Hills, Croydon North and Croydon South. The suburb developed steadily from the 1950s through to the 1990s, producing a housing stock that ranges from original post-war homes on large blocks to 1990s estate developments on subdivided lots. This variety of housing eras means chimney and wood heater configurations vary enormously across the suburb: original open fireplaces in the older sections, early freestanding heaters from the 1970s and 1980s in the middle belt, and more modern slow-combustion installations in the newer sections. Croydon's geography places it in a transition zone between Melbourne's flat eastern suburbs and the rising ground of the Dandenong Ranges foothills. The northern sections — particularly Croydon North and Croydon Hills — sit at higher elevations and are noticeably colder in winter than the suburb's southern areas. Cold air drainage overnight, combined with the altitude effect, means wood fires are a genuine necessity in these sections rather than simply a lifestyle feature. The Croydon Hills area in particular has many properties backing onto bushland reserves, and bird nesting in unused chimneys over summer is extremely common. We regularly service Croydon and all its surrounding pockets, and bird nest removal is a standard part of our inspection process.</p></div>
